Talks Held between Premier of DPRK and Prime Minister of Malaysia 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kuala Lumpur, October 31 (KCNA Correspondent) -- Talks were held between Kim Yong Il, premier of the DPRK Cabinet, and Datuk Seri Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, Prime Minister of Malaysia, in Kuala Lumpur on Oct. 31. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there from the DPRK side were Minister of Foreign Trade Rim Kyong Man, Minister of Agriculture Ri Kyong Sik, Acting Chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries Mun Jae Chol, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Yong Il and DPRK Ambassador to Malaysia Pak Ryong Yon. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there from the Malaysian side were Foreign Minister Datuk Seri Syed Hamid Albar, Secretary General of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs Tan Sri Rastam Mohd Isa, Malaysian Charge d' Affaires a.i. to the DPRK Jamal Sharifuddin Bin Johan and others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the talks both sides exchanged views on the issue of boosting the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries and a series of issues of mutual concern. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The talks proceeded in a friendly atmosphere.

Gu Xiulian Meets Delegation of Rodong Sinmun  
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- Gu Xiulian, vice-chairperson of the Standing Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, met and conversed with the delegation of Rodong Sinmun led by its Deputy Editor-in-Chief Pak Jong Nam on a visit to China at the Great Hall of the People in Beijing on October 30. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Saying that China and the DPRK are friendly neighbors linked with the same mountain and rivers and the Sino-Korean friendship is traditional friendship sealed in blood, she stressed that the Chinese party, government and people attach importance to the friendship, cooperation and exchange with the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The friendship provided by revolutionaries of the elder generation of the two countries has steadily grown stronger under the care of the top leaders of the two countries, she said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 China rejoices over the successes made by the Korean people in the work to develop economy and improve the standard of people's living under the wise leadership of Kim Jong Il and wishes them greater success in the work, she added.

Greetings to Algerian President 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, sent a message of greetings to Abdelaziz Bouteflika, President of the Algerian Democratic and People's Republic, on Oct. 25 on the occasion of the 53rd anniversary of the start of the Algerian revolution. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Reiterating full support and solidarity with the national reconciliation policy of the president and the government of Algeria for the country's stability and unity, Kim in the message expressed the belief that the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would steadily grow stronger.

KCNA Terms Japan's Solicitation Ridiculous 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- Japan is busy with mediocre diplomacy over the "abduction issue".&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Shortly ago, Foreign Minister Komura was reported to have implored the U.S. ambassador to Japan to "shelve the delisting of North Korea as a terrorist sponsor unless progress is made in the settlement of the 'abduction issue.'"&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The "Dietmen's League for the Solution to the Abduction Issue" made up of super-partisan Dietmen also begged other countries to cooperate in the efforts to solve the issue, uttering that it is badly required to put pressure upon the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This is nothing but a crafty and impudent act peculiar to Japan as it is accustomed to pulling up others on the basis of sheer lies. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan is under legal and moral obligations to honestly redress its inglorious past before talking about the "abduction issue" because it brought untold misfortune and pain to the Korean people including the hideous forcible drafting and the crimes related to the "comfort women" for the Imperial Japanese Army. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is preposterous, indeed, for Japan to persistently vociferate about the "abduction issue," which had already found a solution. Irony is that Japan is busy painting itself as a victim, while shutting its eyes to its crime-woven past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's oft-repeated hue and cry over the "abduction issue" is aimed to shirk off its responsibility to redeem its past crimes come what may. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The reality clearly proves that Japan's much touted "abduction issue" would only bring its despicable political and moral nature into bolder relief and invite thorough international isolation.

Academic Degrees or Titles Conferred on Intellectuals 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- DPRK academic degrees or titles were conferred on intellectuals who have made signal contributions to the scientific research and the educational work. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A ceremony of awarding the degrees and titles took place on Tuesday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the ceremony, the title of candidate academician was awarded to Kang Min Gi, a teacher of the University of Science. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 And academic title of professor was conferred on Jong Chang Sik, a researcher of Kim Il Sung University, Pak Ji Min, chief of a department of Kim Chaek University of Technology, Han Yong Gol, a researcher of Pyongyang University of Construction and Building Materials Production, Kwon Thae San, a researcher of Pyongyang University of Foreign Studies, and others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Doctor's degree went to Rim Ho, vice dean of a faculty of Kim Il Sung University, Kim Yong Jo, room chief of Kim Chaek University of Technology, Kim Yun Gyo, chief of a department of Kim Hyong Jik University of Education, and others, title of associate professor to 148 persons and master's degree to 614 persons.

Public Presentation and Academic Symposium Held 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- A scientific and technological presentation in the field of minor power stations and the 3rd national academic symposium on Kyongrak study took place under the sponsorship of the Central Committee of the Korean General Federation of Science and Technology. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants of the public presentation held at Kim Chaek University of Technology heard more than 80 papers on the successful solution of scientific and technological problems arising in the construction and operation of minor power stations which are of weighty significance in settling the nation's problem of acute shortage of electricity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants of the academic symposium on Kyongrak study held at the Academy of Koryo Medicine heard dozens of papers which explained and proved the successes made in the researches into scientifically systematizing the main Kyongrak theory of Koryo medicine and applying it to clinical practice.

Peasant Music and Dance Performance Encouraged in DPRK 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- The Korean people have been fond of peasant music and dance performance from old times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It reflects the aspiration of the peasants to relieve their fatigue and have a good time during breaks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean people had sowed seeds, tended crops and beat back invaders, listening to the peasant music from ancient times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It was called Phungjaeng in a sense of wishing rich harvest, Kolgung in a sense of giving performance tour of villages to raise funds needed for joint work and others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The peasant music and dance performance was also given in sports and amusement games on holidays. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The main instruments for the peasant music included gong, small gong, janggo (a long Korean drum that tapers in the middle), drum and small drum and was supplemented by saenap (a Korean brass wind instrument) in modern ages. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Members of the peasant music and dance performance consist of players of musical instruments and masked dancers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The costume of the performers was the simple peasant one at the first but was changed along with its development in the later half of the Ri Dynasty. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The peasant music and dance performance was given in the form of circle dance, group dance of masked dancers and in the form of dialogic singing and group singing. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The peasant music and dance has developed to suit the modern aesthetic sense. Today it is performed processions celebrating national holidays and at meetings of farms for year-end account settlement and income distribution.

New Kind of Kimchi Good for Health Developed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- Functional kimchi has been recently developed to improve the function of the human body. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The functional kimchi is made with the help of kimchi lactobacilli which has a high capacity of producing gamma-aminobutyric acid. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kimchi is abundant in various kinds of vitamins including vitamins C, B1, B2, B12 and PP, amino acid and minerals needed for the human body. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 With the clarification of the medicinal effect of gamma-aminobutyric acid, kimchi is getting further popular. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The gamma-aminobutyric acid is very efficacious for nervous system control and mental rest function, improvement of liver and kidney-function, immunocyte rejuvenation, pathogenic germ repression function, alcoholysis palpation function and others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Thus it is effective to prevention and treatment for cerebral thrombus, cerebral hemorrhage sequela, hypomnesia and digestive disease. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Foodstuff Research Institute of the Branch Academy of the Light Industrial Science under the State Academy of Sciences succeeded in developing the functional kimchi which is 10 times that of ordinary kimchi in the content of gamma-aminobutyric acid and thus developed the quality of kimchi on a higher stage. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The newly developed functional kimchi is tasty and incomparably superior to other kinds of kimchi in its medicinal function for health.

Over 170 Cases of Aerial Espionage Committed against DPRK
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 31 (KCNA) -- More than 170 cases of aerial espionage were committed against the DPRK in October of which over 110 by the U.S. imperialist aggression forces and more than 60 by the south Korean forces, according to a military source. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A south Korea-based U-2 perpetrated 25 cases of aerial espionage against the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. imperialists sent 3 or 4 RC-7Bs and RC-12s to the air over the areas along the Military Demarcation Line (MDL) every day for aerial observation and photographing of the areas of the DPRK side. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On Oct. 19 an overseas-based RC-135 flew in the air over south Korea to perpetrate aerial espionage against the DPRK. Overseas based EP-3 committed similar acts on Oct. 15 and 17. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The south Korean military warlike forces let RC-800s and RF-4Cs fly every day to perpetrate various acts of espionage against the areas along the MDL of the DPRK side. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ceaseless aerial espionage committed by the U.S. imperialists and the south Korean military bellicose forces against the DPRK are a blatant challenge to the "Declaration for the development of north-south relations and peace and prosperity." This clearly indicates that they are pursuing aggression and war only.

